7.1 Mouse Button Events
=======================

Mouse event handlers are defined by giving 'button' to
'cheerilee-defevent'.

   In this case, the macro exposes the following variables:

 -- Variable: this
     The element that received the event.

 -- Variable: x
     Where the event is located horizontally, starting from the top-left
     corner of the application frame and going right.

 -- Variable: y
     Where the event is located vertically, starting from the top-left
     corner of the application frame and going down.

 -- Variable: detail
     The button pressed, as a number.

 -- Variable: tree
     The application that received the event.

   After defining the handler, you can use it for two types of events:

 -- Function: cheerilee-add-button-press-event tree id fun
     This function associate FUN, an event handler, with _every_ element
     called ID in TREE.  This method will be called when any mouse
     button is pressed.

     For example, calling

          (cheerilee-add-button-press-event appl "ID" #'mouse-event-function)

     will associate 'mouse-event-function' with every element called
     "ID" inside 'appl'.

 -- Function: cheerilee-add-button-release-event tree id fun
     This function works the same as 'cheerilee-add-button-press-event',
     with the difference that FUN is called when any mouse button is
     released.


