7.2 Keyboard Events
===================

Keyboard event handlers are defined by giving 'keyboard' to
'cheerilee-defevent'.

   In this case, the macro exposes the following variables:

 -- Variable: this
     The element that received the event.

 -- Variable: detail
     The button pressed, as a number.  This value is the keycode given
     by the X server.  Keycodes are hardware-oriented, to have a more
     usable value, e.g.  to compare it with ASCII decimal values, you
     need to convert it to a keysym, with a function explained later in
     the section.

 -- Variable: modifier
     Any special button pressed together with 'detail', like <CTRL> or
     <META>.

 -- Variable: tree
     The application that received the event.

   After defining the handler, you can use it for two types of events:

 -- Function: cheerilee-add-key-press-event tree id fun
     This function associate FUN, an event handler, with _every_ element
     called ID in TREE.  This method will be called when any keyboard
     button is pressed.

     For example, calling

          (cheerilee-add-key-press-event appl "ID" #'keyboard-event-function)

     will associate 'keyboard-event-function' with every element called
     "ID" inside 'appl'.

 -- Function: cheerilee-add-key-release-event tree id fun
     This function works the same as 'cheerilee-add-key-press-event',
     with the difference that FUN is called when any keyboard button is
     released.

   To convert a keycode to a keysym, you use the following function:

 -- Function: cheerilee-keycode-to-keysym detail modifier
     This function converts a keycode to a keysym.  The keysym can then
     be used to check for specific key press.


